WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:10.000
From the Library of Congress and the Smithsonian National Museum of African American History and Culture.

00:00:10.000 --> 00:00:16.000
My name is Emilye Crosby and today is December 1, 2015.

00:00:16.000 --> 00:00:29.000
And I'm here with Thames to Clarence McGee and we're at the University of Southern Mississippi from the McCain Library at the Royal History and Cultural Heritage Center.

00:00:29.000 --> 00:00:37.000
The Center for the History and Cultural Heritage with me is John Bishop, who with us is John Bishop and Guha Shankar.

00:00:37.000 --> 00:00:48.000
And we're here with the Civil Rights History Project, which is co-sponsored by the Library of Congress and the National, the Smithsonian National Museum on African American History and Culture.

00:00:48.000 --> 00:00:52.000
So thank you very much, Mr. McGee, for joining us today.

00:00:52.000 --> 00:00:54.000
You're welcome.

00:00:55.000 --> 00:01:03.000
I was wondering if you'd be willing to start by talking about when and where you were born and about your family.

00:01:03.000 --> 00:01:21.000
I was born and Marion County, Columbia, Mississippi, in 1900 and, well, May 15, 1932.

00:01:21.000 --> 00:01:29.000
I have two birth dates. I have May 14, which is officially by my mother's record because she was there.

00:01:29.000 --> 00:01:31.000
She would have something to invest in.

00:01:31.000 --> 00:01:35.000
Of course, the federal government came in late and said it's the 15.

00:01:35.000 --> 00:01:40.000
In order to get benefits, I say 15, but I celebrate the 14.

00:01:40.000 --> 00:01:42.000
Okay?

00:01:42.000 --> 00:01:46.000
You're going to say, when you do it, you get all the energy.

00:01:46.000 --> 00:01:48.000
So you have two birth dates.

00:01:48.000 --> 00:01:51.000
I have two birth dates, of course.

00:01:51.000 --> 00:01:52.000
Yeah.

00:01:52.000 --> 00:02:05.000
And I'm the oldest of 10 siblings, five boys, five girls.

00:02:05.000 --> 00:02:10.000
One of the girls have deceased two of the boys have passed on.

00:02:10.000 --> 00:02:13.000
So they still leave seven of us.

00:02:13.000 --> 00:02:14.000
Yeah.

00:02:14.000 --> 00:02:20.000
And all at one time were married.

00:02:20.000 --> 00:02:27.000
We all have children, you know, from two to five.

00:02:27.000 --> 00:02:41.000
My parents are the late Glessie R. McGee and O'Reilly, Leggett McGee.

00:02:42.000 --> 00:02:47.000
We grew up in the rural area of Marion County.

00:02:47.000 --> 00:02:51.000
My dad initially was a sharecropper.

00:02:51.000 --> 00:03:02.000
And he vowed before he ever married, if he had children, that he would make sure that they went to school.

00:03:02.000 --> 00:03:08.000
So our money crop, for the most part, was cotton.

00:03:09.000 --> 00:03:17.000
He eventually ended up purchasing photo acres of land with maybe about three acres for call.

00:03:17.000 --> 00:03:19.000
That could be cultivated.

00:03:19.000 --> 00:03:23.000
And he took an axe and he cleared off the new ground.

00:03:23.000 --> 00:03:31.000
And we would come in after school and pick up the limbs and pile them up and burn them.

00:03:31.000 --> 00:03:40.000
That, the portion that we didn't use for heating our home and preparing our meals.

00:03:40.000 --> 00:03:49.000
I came up when there was no switch that you can flip and the heat come on, or the light comes on, or turn a faucet and get water.

00:03:49.000 --> 00:03:54.000
All of that sort of come like out of the natural.

00:03:54.000 --> 00:03:57.000
We were nature people.

00:03:57.000 --> 00:04:00.000
We never went hungry.

00:04:00.000 --> 00:04:07.000
We always had plenty to eat, not a big variety, because we grew everything.

00:04:07.000 --> 00:04:16.000
We raised chickens, therefore we had our eggs and our chicken for eating and re-raised cows.

00:04:16.000 --> 00:04:21.000
Therefore we had our milk and beef.

00:04:21.000 --> 00:04:26.000
We raised hogs, therefore we had our pork.

00:04:26.000 --> 00:04:32.000
We grew corn. We had to gather that for the winter.

00:04:32.000 --> 00:04:37.000
We re-sweep potatoes. We have the galodos and bank them for the winter.

00:04:37.000 --> 00:04:46.000
We got water from a spring.

00:04:46.000 --> 00:04:49.000
Buckets or peels go down under the hill.

00:04:49.000 --> 00:05:02.000
Packed the water back up the hills for drinking, for cooking, for bathing, for washing clothes, for feeding the lifestyle.

00:05:02.000 --> 00:05:06.000
I guess that we're giving them, instead of not to waste the water.

00:05:06.000 --> 00:05:14.000
It's insanity not to waste water, but it also developed a sort of discipline to work.

00:05:14.000 --> 00:05:18.000
We grew up having to work because of necessity.

00:05:18.000 --> 00:05:20.000
Everybody had to do that.

00:05:20.000 --> 00:05:22.000
They're old-share.

00:05:22.000 --> 00:05:26.000
Once you got big enough, you knew what you were supposed to do.

00:05:26.000 --> 00:05:31.000
You tried to do it before, dark, because we had no electricity.

00:05:31.000 --> 00:05:33.000
We had lamps.

00:05:33.000 --> 00:05:35.000
We had fireplace.

00:05:35.000 --> 00:05:38.000
We'd get down in front of a fireplace and do our studies.

00:05:38.000 --> 00:05:50.000
I used, recall, you set up a pale and put some fat and candles on top of it to make a fire.

00:05:50.000 --> 00:05:55.000
You can start it by that.

00:05:55.000 --> 00:05:59.000
My dad may have been promoted to the sixth grade.

00:05:59.000 --> 00:06:04.000
I've seen my mother actually experienced the sixth grade.

00:06:05.000 --> 00:06:10.000
However, they didn't have the academic learning.

00:06:10.000 --> 00:06:19.000
They had what older people call the fifth, they call it mother with that.

00:06:19.000 --> 00:06:24.000
My dad was a very good trainer.

00:06:24.000 --> 00:06:29.000
I used to train intentionally.

00:06:29.000 --> 00:06:32.000
He taught us what to do, how to do it.

00:06:32.000 --> 00:06:38.000
If we did not do it correctly, he taught us what we needed to do it to do it.

00:06:38.000 --> 00:06:43.000
It was better to do job well, not do it at all.

00:06:43.000 --> 00:06:48.000
Why spend extra time doing the same job a second time?

00:06:48.000 --> 00:06:51.000
We learned real fast from his training.

00:06:51.000 --> 00:06:57.000
He always encouraged us to read and to study.

00:06:57.000 --> 00:07:06.000
My mother worked as a houseperson and a mother.

00:07:06.000 --> 00:07:13.000
And in the field, chopping and holding cotton and corn and picking cotton.

00:07:13.000 --> 00:07:16.000
Up until, say, about 10-13 or 11 o'clock,

00:07:16.000 --> 00:07:21.000
leave the field, come home, prepare meals so that when we came home,

00:07:21.000 --> 00:07:26.000
there was food for us to eat.

00:07:26.000 --> 00:07:33.000
I might be going a little to four right now, but as it comes to my gesture of love on you.

00:07:33.000 --> 00:07:39.000
You mentioned that your parents, your father might have finished sixth grade

00:07:39.000 --> 00:07:42.000
and your mother, you weren't sure if she experienced sixth grade.

00:07:42.000 --> 00:07:44.000
That's the reverse.

00:07:44.000 --> 00:07:45.000
I got it wrong.

00:07:45.000 --> 00:07:47.000
Yeah, just the reverse.

00:07:47.000 --> 00:07:51.000
Did they miss not going further in school?

00:07:51.000 --> 00:07:52.000
They did.

00:07:52.000 --> 00:08:05.000
My dad, and of course, when he was younger, his dad was only on the form,

00:08:05.000 --> 00:08:11.000
but then he did extra work in order to take them through the window months.

00:08:12.000 --> 00:08:18.000
My dad tells the story about his dad promising he and his sister.

00:08:18.000 --> 00:08:25.000
If you worked real well this week and come next Monday,

00:08:25.000 --> 00:08:27.000
you guys can go to school.

00:08:27.000 --> 00:08:30.000
They were excited about it.

00:08:30.000 --> 00:08:32.000
So they got up early that Monday morning.

00:08:32.000 --> 00:08:37.000
They took care of their wall and chores and got dressed and they sat on the porch

00:08:37.000 --> 00:08:40.000
and went like, here's that awake.

00:08:40.000 --> 00:08:45.000
He said to my grandma at that time, says, get those chores on up

00:08:45.000 --> 00:08:48.000
because we got to go do some work.

00:08:48.000 --> 00:08:50.000
See, so the chores were up there on the porch.

00:08:50.000 --> 00:08:53.000
They were waiting to go to school.

00:08:53.000 --> 00:08:56.000
Sorry, ain't nobody going to school here today.

00:08:56.000 --> 00:09:01.000
I just made a contract with this guy to clean up a new ground.

00:09:01.000 --> 00:09:05.000
That means I'm going to take an axe, I'm going to cut down the trees and the bushes and all that.

00:09:06.000 --> 00:09:09.000
They got to go out there and pick them up and burn it.

00:09:09.000 --> 00:09:11.000
Brought my dad his heart.

00:09:11.000 --> 00:09:17.000
Made a vow that the L.I. had children, that they would go to school.

00:09:17.000 --> 00:09:21.000
Did you have trouble keeping you on school?

00:09:21.000 --> 00:09:23.000
Did you have a sacrifice?

00:09:23.000 --> 00:09:25.000
No, it was not a sacrifice.

00:09:25.000 --> 00:09:33.000
In elementary school and junior high high school, we enjoyed going to school.

00:09:33.000 --> 00:09:41.000
It was a little bit a different style of life because we worked hard in the fields

00:09:41.000 --> 00:09:46.000
and we worked hard to get everything done so that we could go to school.

00:09:46.000 --> 00:09:56.000
Our lifestyle, having to do things inspired us to want to do something different.

00:09:56.000 --> 00:10:02.000
We were not afraid of school, we wanted to go to school.

00:10:02.000 --> 00:10:07.000
Once we finished high school, we might have been a little hesitant there.

00:10:07.000 --> 00:10:13.000
He said to us, they would come a day when high school diploma will not be good enough.

00:10:13.000 --> 00:10:16.000
They got to go further.

00:10:16.000 --> 00:10:24.000
Of course, I'm the oldest, of course, so I'm the first who went to high school.

00:10:24.000 --> 00:10:30.000
I went with the college, went further than high school.

00:10:30.000 --> 00:10:32.000
I had some, a few setbacks.

00:10:32.000 --> 00:10:37.000
I was in the All Corn A&M college.

00:10:37.000 --> 00:10:40.000
It's All Corn State University now.

00:10:40.000 --> 00:10:47.000
30 days to the day of my mother passed from childbirth,

00:10:47.000 --> 00:10:52.000
which was a total wreck of my life.

00:10:52.000 --> 00:10:58.000
I had to get the bus from Alcorn State University, Mississippi.

00:10:58.000 --> 00:11:04.000
Someone took me from Alcorn State University, Mississippi to Vicksburg, Mississippi to get the bus.

00:11:04.000 --> 00:11:09.000
The bus from Vicksburg, Mississippi took me all day to get to Columbia.

00:11:09.000 --> 00:11:13.000
My dad and my aunt commit me at the bus station.

00:11:13.000 --> 00:11:18.000
After the fuel, my dad says, if you want to go back, you can go back.

00:11:18.000 --> 00:11:20.000
I had a choice.

00:11:20.000 --> 00:11:22.000
I chose to go back.

00:11:22.000 --> 00:11:28.000
Of course, I was not in any condition to make my grades.

00:11:28.000 --> 00:11:32.000
I basically failed, but we had the second semester.

00:11:32.000 --> 00:11:36.000
I sort of pulled myself together in that past.

00:11:36.000 --> 00:11:42.000
The other tragedy that happened was just about one month into the second semester.

00:11:42.000 --> 00:11:48.000
My dad came down with a diabetic or coma.

00:11:48.000 --> 00:11:52.000
I didn't know he was diabetic, but my sister, who was there,

00:11:52.000 --> 00:12:01.000
not who was next to me, was sort of like the person who kept everything together with my dad.

00:12:01.000 --> 00:12:06.000
She said, my dad took ill and he couldn't lie down.

00:12:06.000 --> 00:12:08.000
He couldn't sit up.

00:12:08.000 --> 00:12:16.000
He was sitting in my younger siblings to the field.

00:12:16.000 --> 00:12:23.000
The time of the year that you could take a hole and cut up the cool and stalks.

00:12:23.000 --> 00:12:26.000
That's what they do, getting prepared.

00:12:26.000 --> 00:12:28.000
He sent them out one door.

00:12:28.000 --> 00:12:31.000
She went out to the back door and accepted them.

00:12:31.000 --> 00:12:34.000
They said, no, go get my grandma.

00:12:34.000 --> 00:12:36.000
Maybe three miles away.

00:12:36.000 --> 00:12:38.000
They went to my grandmother.

00:12:38.000 --> 00:12:41.000
My grandmother got a first customer man who had a car.

00:12:41.000 --> 00:12:43.000
Came to pick my daddy up.

00:12:43.000 --> 00:12:49.000
When they moved him from the bed to the car, that's when he went into a coma.

00:12:49.000 --> 00:12:53.000
They took him to the hospital.

00:12:53.000 --> 00:13:03.000
When he got the diabetes down on us so he could talk and everything.

00:13:03.000 --> 00:13:06.000
He asked the doctor to get ready to release him.

00:13:06.000 --> 00:13:08.000
He said, what must I do now?

00:13:08.000 --> 00:13:10.000
I go back home.

00:13:10.000 --> 00:13:11.000
He said, you don't go home.

00:13:11.000 --> 00:13:12.000
Sit down.

00:13:12.000 --> 00:13:16.000
You go home and work as hard as you ever work.

00:13:16.000 --> 00:13:19.000
Then he put them on a diet.

00:13:19.000 --> 00:13:23.000
Pretty much oatmeal.

00:13:23.000 --> 00:13:26.000
No sugar.

00:13:26.000 --> 00:13:34.000
I think he had the drawer in the table.

00:13:34.000 --> 00:13:39.000
It would tell me whether the glucose was up or low.

00:13:39.000 --> 00:13:44.000
But he graduated from that.

00:13:44.000 --> 00:13:50.000
Eventually, it went in remission.

00:13:50.000 --> 00:13:53.000
He lived to be like 84 years of age.

00:13:53.000 --> 00:13:55.000
He died of diabetes.

00:13:55.000 --> 00:14:01.000
He died of congestive heart failure.

00:14:01.000 --> 00:14:11.000
All that tied into my school, I could have said after my mother passed, I'm satisfied.

00:14:11.000 --> 00:14:14.000
That would have been a terrible mistake.

00:14:14.000 --> 00:14:15.000
I could have said that.

00:14:15.000 --> 00:14:19.000
I had to come home when daddy went to Nabil and stayed a whole week.

00:14:19.000 --> 00:14:24.000
When he came back, if you want to go back, you can go back.

00:14:24.000 --> 00:14:26.000
I think God I had the courage to go back.

00:14:26.000 --> 00:14:30.000
I was there to finish.

00:14:30.000 --> 00:14:37.000
That's tied in with their education and how we were motivated to go to schools and get degrees.

00:14:37.000 --> 00:14:42.000
My daddy eventually married a couple of years after my mother died.

00:14:42.000 --> 00:14:44.000
A person who was a teacher.

00:14:44.000 --> 00:14:46.000
Of course, she had no children of her own.

00:14:46.000 --> 00:14:55.000
That left by O. DeSister and two other sisters there, two brothers there.

00:14:55.000 --> 00:14:58.000
What happened to the other brother and the other sister?

00:14:58.000 --> 00:15:06.000
When we grew up there, we were across the lane from my dad's mother, my grandmother.

00:15:06.000 --> 00:15:09.000
We loved to stay at Grandmomma's house.

00:15:09.000 --> 00:15:13.000
My older brother loved to stay there more than anybody else.

00:15:13.000 --> 00:15:20.000
When we finally moved from there to the property, my mother would not take this boy.

00:15:20.000 --> 00:15:23.000
She let him stay there.

00:15:23.000 --> 00:15:31.000
She raised him and when my mother passed, the two young siblings were a girl.

00:15:31.000 --> 00:15:37.000
The baby was 18 months old and the other girl had to be in four years old.

00:15:37.000 --> 00:15:47.000
My grandma took them in between her death and my dad had to get themselves out of the house.

00:15:47.000 --> 00:15:51.000
She ended up raising those two girls.

00:15:51.000 --> 00:15:55.000
She raised my older brother, two girls.

00:15:55.000 --> 00:16:02.000
My older brother, when he got out of high school, he volunteered to go to the home service.

00:16:02.000 --> 00:16:05.000
That left her with no boy.

00:16:05.000 --> 00:16:11.000
She came to my dad's house and said, I came to get a boy.

00:16:11.000 --> 00:16:16.000
My baby brother was there, heard it.

00:16:16.000 --> 00:16:18.000
He volunteered.

00:16:18.000 --> 00:16:25.000
She took him, but then when she got him by home, she discovered he had not been trained to plow.

00:16:25.000 --> 00:16:33.000
She took him to trade him off to get the other brother.

00:16:33.000 --> 00:16:38.000
The baby brother cried and said, that's okay, I'll keep you.

00:16:38.000 --> 00:16:44.000
She ended up raising four months in for my family.

00:16:44.000 --> 00:16:48.000
They could not go into place without permission from my dad.

00:16:48.000 --> 00:16:51.000
My grandma would whip.

00:16:51.000 --> 00:16:55.000
If you did something that you really need to whip me, I'm just going to tell your dad.

00:16:55.000 --> 00:16:56.000
How far away did you go?

00:16:56.000 --> 00:16:59.000
About three miles after that.

00:16:59.000 --> 00:17:02.000
Three miles is further than it is.

00:17:02.000 --> 00:17:06.000
It was close to the end.

00:17:06.000 --> 00:17:10.000
We could run three miles.

00:17:10.000 --> 00:17:13.000
Exactly.

00:17:13.000 --> 00:17:19.000
We could run three miles across the field, across the past and get there.

00:17:19.000 --> 00:17:27.000
I was wondering, not many people of your generation had the opportunity to go to college.

00:17:27.000 --> 00:17:29.000
Sometimes they had to work.

00:17:29.000 --> 00:17:37.000
I know you were working, but was it hard for your father to give up your labor to go to college or even to attend school every day?

00:17:37.000 --> 00:17:41.000
I don't think it was.

00:17:41.000 --> 00:17:44.000
It was not for hard for him to give it up.

00:17:44.000 --> 00:17:47.000
It just made the adjustment.

00:17:47.000 --> 00:17:52.000
I plowed on you.

00:17:52.000 --> 00:17:58.000
It was so interesting going to school.

00:17:58.000 --> 00:18:04.000
He would have to say to me, don't you burn my mule out.

00:18:04.000 --> 00:18:10.000
You take a fur, you go to the other end, when you get to the end, you don't do it the laser wave.

00:18:10.000 --> 00:18:12.000
Just stand there and pull them.

00:18:12.000 --> 00:18:15.000
You pick up your plow and you make a swing.

00:18:15.000 --> 00:18:17.000
The mule turn, you turn.

00:18:17.000 --> 00:18:18.000
Boom.

00:18:18.000 --> 00:18:20.000
You're going back the other way.

00:18:20.000 --> 00:18:21.000
You're the same thing.

00:18:21.000 --> 00:18:22.000
Boom.

00:18:22.000 --> 00:18:26.000
A mule doesn't know when he's too hard or not too hard.

00:18:26.000 --> 00:18:28.000
He had the caution.

00:18:28.000 --> 00:18:31.000
Don't you get them, you're too hard.

00:18:31.000 --> 00:18:38.000
When I left and went to college, I left one, two, three boys initially at the house.

00:18:38.000 --> 00:18:44.000
Then I remember when my dad finally got a tractor, which I never got an experience to use.

00:18:44.000 --> 00:18:48.000
He made it with that by having a tractor.

00:18:48.000 --> 00:18:52.000
After the tractor, all of us had moved out.

00:18:52.000 --> 00:18:56.000
He started a cattle instead of cotton.

00:18:56.000 --> 00:18:59.000
He had at least 30 or 40 here in the cow.

00:18:59.000 --> 00:19:02.000
Of course, that kept him close because he had to wash them at all the time.

00:19:02.000 --> 00:19:07.000
He never knew who in a car if he was going to drop or when he had to get a vet in there

00:19:07.000 --> 00:19:09.000
and come in to take care of the cows.

00:19:09.000 --> 00:19:15.000
Then, of course, he finally got out of that and he did what he loved, even though that was a fish.

00:19:15.000 --> 00:19:18.000
My dad, I never knew that you loved the fish.

00:19:18.000 --> 00:19:20.000
When I was a boy, we never went.

00:19:20.000 --> 00:19:25.000
The only time we went to fish, we went down on the creek and it was thick.

00:19:25.000 --> 00:19:26.000
It was hot.

00:19:26.000 --> 00:19:28.000
A lot of mosquitoes and the snakes.

00:19:28.000 --> 00:19:35.000
If you didn't catch anything, you went down there to catch a meal, but you came by starving.

00:19:35.000 --> 00:19:40.000
He said, I couldn't take a chance or maybe going to fish.

00:19:40.000 --> 00:19:44.000
I had to do whatever produced the food right now.

00:19:44.000 --> 00:19:47.000
It turned out to be a really good fish and he loved it.

00:19:47.000 --> 00:19:48.000
He loved it.

00:19:48.000 --> 00:19:49.000
He loved it.

00:19:49.000 --> 00:19:50.000
He loved it.

00:19:50.000 --> 00:19:53.000
That's schooling now.

00:19:53.000 --> 00:20:04.000
The biggest training that my dad gave his children was picking cotton is a hot job.

00:20:04.000 --> 00:20:07.000
Pick a cotton.

00:20:07.000 --> 00:20:13.000
There's a slight in doing everything to make it easy.

00:20:13.000 --> 00:20:15.000
Cotton grows in burrs.

00:20:15.000 --> 00:20:18.000
You reach for a cotton out of the burr.

00:20:18.000 --> 00:20:20.000
You make sure you get it the first time.

00:20:20.000 --> 00:20:23.000
You can't be going two and three times in that burr.

00:20:23.000 --> 00:20:25.000
One burr.

00:20:25.000 --> 00:20:33.000
He would pay us one penny per pound.

00:20:33.000 --> 00:20:38.000
If I picked 100 pounds a cotton a day, I earned a dollar for the whole day.

