00:35:52.000 --> 00:35:54.000
there was one full-class, seven-graders,

00:35:54.000 --> 00:35:56.000
one-foot, six-graders.

00:35:56.000 --> 00:35:59.000
And the overflow I had come by.

00:35:59.000 --> 00:36:03.000
So I did that probably like three years.

00:36:03.000 --> 00:36:05.000
And then when Lillie Burney School School opened,

00:36:05.000 --> 00:36:08.000
I went to Lillie Burney School School as well.

00:36:08.000 --> 00:36:11.000
And I left Lillie Burney School School in 1969,

00:36:11.000 --> 00:36:15.000
and I went to Rowan high school.

00:36:15.000 --> 00:36:18.000
And I left there.

00:36:18.000 --> 00:36:22.000
I went with the Southern Mississippi Platinum Development District

00:36:22.000 --> 00:36:25.000
for approximately two years.

00:36:25.000 --> 00:36:28.000
And after that in between that,

00:36:28.000 --> 00:36:32.000
I got employment with the Federal Government Department of Agriculture,

00:36:32.000 --> 00:36:34.000
Food and Consumer Service.

00:36:34.000 --> 00:36:36.000
I retired from them.

00:36:36.000 --> 00:36:38.000
But in order to take that job,

00:36:38.000 --> 00:36:40.000
I needed to move to Mobile.

00:36:40.000 --> 00:36:43.000
So that's when I went to Mobile in 74.

00:36:43.000 --> 00:36:50.000
And I worked from 74 to 95.

00:36:50.000 --> 00:36:52.000
Came back to Hattiesburg, Mississippi.

00:36:52.000 --> 00:36:54.000
But I was still in the same job,

00:36:54.000 --> 00:36:57.000
but my office was located in Jackson.

00:36:57.000 --> 00:37:00.000
So I worked there about three years before I retired.

00:37:00.000 --> 00:37:01.000
You knew Jackson?

00:37:01.000 --> 00:37:02.000
Yeah.

00:37:02.000 --> 00:37:05.000
And it was not bad because at that time,

00:37:05.000 --> 00:37:07.000
we had to start working,

00:37:07.000 --> 00:37:11.000
compress hours, ten hours a day, four days a week.

00:37:11.000 --> 00:37:13.000
So you didn't have to go five days?

00:37:13.000 --> 00:37:15.000
I didn't have to go five days.

00:37:15.000 --> 00:37:19.000
But that program started when I was in Mobile.

00:37:19.000 --> 00:37:25.000
The day the staff decided what days they were going to take off,

00:37:25.000 --> 00:37:27.000
I was in the field.

00:37:27.000 --> 00:37:30.000
And so when I came back,

00:37:30.000 --> 00:37:33.000
and that was Monday.

00:37:33.000 --> 00:37:34.000
Can you believe Monday?

00:37:34.000 --> 00:37:36.000
I go to work.

00:37:36.000 --> 00:37:38.000
I have Monday off.

00:37:38.000 --> 00:37:41.000
I go to still Wednesday Thursday and Friday.

00:37:41.000 --> 00:37:44.000
So I leave here on Tuesday morning.

00:37:44.000 --> 00:37:48.000
It's been Tuesday night, Wednesday night, Thursday night with my sister.

00:37:48.000 --> 00:37:49.000
Friday I'm back at home.

00:37:49.000 --> 00:37:53.000
Friday night, Saturday night, Sunday night, Monday night, home.

00:37:53.000 --> 00:37:55.000
That's a pretty good situation.

00:37:55.000 --> 00:37:59.000
Godless half of people who are...

00:37:59.000 --> 00:38:01.000
Facing.

00:38:01.000 --> 00:38:05.000
Whatever you're doing, you're doing.

00:38:05.000 --> 00:38:10.000
I could probably go back and figure it out.

00:38:10.000 --> 00:38:13.000
So did you move the handlebar like in the late fifth?

00:38:13.000 --> 00:38:15.000
Fifty-six.

00:38:15.000 --> 00:38:23.000
So were you willing to service them when the round decision came?

00:38:23.000 --> 00:38:24.000
Oh yes.

00:38:24.000 --> 00:38:25.000
A good fact.

00:38:25.000 --> 00:38:30.000
Was that something that you were thinking about or aware of at the time?

00:38:30.000 --> 00:38:33.000
I was aware of it.

00:38:33.000 --> 00:38:36.000
Since it was over young, it was not here.

00:38:36.000 --> 00:38:40.000
So you're not at that age, you're not a whole lot concerned about.

00:38:40.000 --> 00:38:42.000
I was aware of it.

00:38:42.000 --> 00:38:44.000
How did you...

00:38:44.000 --> 00:38:54.000
Like, what was your first sort of awareness of race?

00:38:54.000 --> 00:38:59.000
Since I was about eight and a half years old, I guess.

00:38:59.000 --> 00:39:00.000
Sure.

00:39:00.000 --> 00:39:02.000
Is that going to town?

00:39:02.000 --> 00:39:05.000
Going to town, but look.

00:39:05.000 --> 00:39:14.000
In the south, the relationship between a black family and a white family could be just like this.

00:39:14.000 --> 00:39:17.000
That's not race.

00:39:17.000 --> 00:39:25.000
My dad is share crowd with the white family who taught school in the school year.

00:39:25.000 --> 00:39:33.000
And during this school year, we could move from our house to their house,

00:39:33.000 --> 00:39:39.000
which was tight, had windows and huge fireplace.

00:39:39.000 --> 00:39:41.000
And we could...

00:39:41.000 --> 00:39:46.000
In the springtime, we go back to our house, which was up off the ground,

00:39:46.000 --> 00:39:49.000
had shutters for windows,

00:39:49.000 --> 00:40:00.000
had a huge living room and a kitchen, not holes in the floor, pick it roof on top,

00:40:00.000 --> 00:40:02.000
we'll crack send it.

00:40:02.000 --> 00:40:07.000
So when a rain came down, you had to put peels out to catch the water.

00:40:07.000 --> 00:40:10.000
When we lived in their house, doing their abs and out of...

00:40:10.000 --> 00:40:12.000
We didn't have that problem.

00:40:12.000 --> 00:40:16.000
We could hear the wind outside, you know, whistling that kind of...

00:40:16.000 --> 00:40:19.000
But in our house, we could feel the winds.

00:40:19.000 --> 00:40:22.000
Yeah, you know, cracks in the wall.

00:40:22.000 --> 00:40:28.000
The wall became our library because they were used newspaper, not newspaper.

00:40:28.000 --> 00:40:30.000
Yeah, and cover them up with.

00:40:30.000 --> 00:40:34.000
So we see pictures from study.

00:40:34.000 --> 00:40:36.000
And then when it...

00:40:36.000 --> 00:40:43.000
And the fall of the year before we moved there, we could touch the goats through the nother...

00:40:43.000 --> 00:40:46.000
The pigs, through the nother, you know.

00:40:46.000 --> 00:40:55.000
So it was a relationship there that we didn't have when we went to town.

00:40:55.000 --> 00:41:01.000
I can remember clearly, on two occasions, one time I was downtown, very young.

00:41:01.000 --> 00:41:09.000
I walked into something like a pool hall and people of color, they're going there.

00:41:09.000 --> 00:41:12.000
They're wondering what they're doing in front of us.

00:41:12.000 --> 00:41:14.000
And they are in the car.

00:41:14.000 --> 00:41:17.000
Many issue me out the back door.

00:41:17.000 --> 00:41:20.000
But, you know, back on the street, nothing happened.

00:41:20.000 --> 00:41:23.000
And I remember once walking down the street in the car coming.

00:41:23.000 --> 00:41:35.000
I don't know how close, but it was with inches of hit and it didn't get you to look at that close.

00:41:35.000 --> 00:41:45.000
And when we would go to work from my house, we had to pass right by the family my dad is sharecrawled with.

00:41:45.000 --> 00:41:52.000
If we ate at that house, we ate on the back porch within eight inside our house.

00:41:52.000 --> 00:41:54.000
We sit on the back porch.

00:41:54.000 --> 00:41:58.000
This is the family where you would sit in their house.

00:41:58.000 --> 00:42:01.000
So you have to live in their house, but when they were there, you would eat on the back porch.

00:42:01.000 --> 00:42:02.000
Yeah.

00:42:02.000 --> 00:42:06.000
Would they ever eat at your house?

00:42:06.000 --> 00:42:07.000
No.

00:42:07.000 --> 00:42:15.000
So, you watch what your parent did or did not do.

00:42:15.000 --> 00:42:23.000
And they may, I mean, not say anything, but you tell by that action that there are some places you don't go.

00:42:23.000 --> 00:42:25.000
Or some things you don't say.

00:42:25.000 --> 00:42:30.000
So, you learn to follow the leaders.

00:42:30.000 --> 00:42:32.000
You got good leaders.

00:42:32.000 --> 00:42:34.000
So, you're aware of it.

00:42:34.000 --> 00:42:41.000
Of course, now I'm direct experience and participation is two different things.

00:42:41.000 --> 00:42:42.000
You know.

00:42:42.000 --> 00:42:46.000
And that's what I'm going to say.

00:42:46.000 --> 00:42:53.000
So, what first cut you, what was your first awareness of the civil rights movement?

00:42:53.000 --> 00:43:05.000
1956, when my dad and my wife purchased our first home.

00:43:05.000 --> 00:43:14.000
He said to me, now that you own a home, you can pay a $2 poll tack and you can register to vote.

00:43:14.000 --> 00:43:17.000
I'm not sure that he's registered at this time.

00:43:17.000 --> 00:43:20.000
That was actually the one, then, yeah.

00:43:20.000 --> 00:43:23.000
So, he's telling you about it.

00:43:23.000 --> 00:43:25.000
He's telling me about it.

00:43:25.000 --> 00:43:29.000
So, you own a home, you got to pay property tax.

00:43:29.000 --> 00:43:34.000
Every time I go pay my property tax, I pay my poll tax.

00:43:34.000 --> 00:43:43.000
So, I started going to the clerk office, exercising my right because I pay poll tax to register to vote.

00:43:43.000 --> 00:43:49.000
You get caught off guard.

00:43:49.000 --> 00:44:00.000
The first time I went in, a deputy clerk met me at the desk and asked what I wanted.

00:44:00.000 --> 00:44:06.000
I told the other members, he said the register is not in today.

00:44:06.000 --> 00:44:08.000
Well, what is his hours?

00:44:08.000 --> 00:44:11.000
Well, he didn't keep regular hours.

00:44:11.000 --> 00:44:13.000
So, what am I supposed to do?

00:44:13.000 --> 00:44:16.000
She walk away, and I'm not going to stand up.

00:44:16.000 --> 00:44:17.000
That's all I walk away.

00:44:17.000 --> 00:44:21.000
It's 12 months probably later, I go back and do this lane, go through this lane routine.

00:44:21.000 --> 00:44:23.000
This time he's in.

00:44:23.000 --> 00:44:28.000
His name is, come on up there and lean.

00:44:28.000 --> 00:44:31.000
Who went before him?

00:44:31.000 --> 00:44:32.000
Cox.

00:44:32.000 --> 00:44:33.000
Yes.

00:44:34.000 --> 00:44:39.000
I met the same deputy at the Caroline, she says, what do you want?

00:44:39.000 --> 00:44:46.000
I told her, she called him from the back, he walked up, I'm standing there, he says, what do you want, boy?

00:44:46.000 --> 00:44:49.000
I told her, who sent you, boy?

00:44:49.000 --> 00:44:51.000
I said, nobody.

00:44:51.000 --> 00:44:53.000
You better wait.

00:44:53.000 --> 00:44:55.000
He walks away.

00:44:55.000 --> 00:44:57.000
I walk away.

00:44:57.000 --> 00:45:01.000
The next time I go by, you know, you're in a row.

00:45:01.000 --> 00:45:04.000
How did you feel?

00:45:04.000 --> 00:45:08.000
I didn't feel the best at that time.

00:45:08.000 --> 00:45:13.000
You're like a shock treatment.

00:45:13.000 --> 00:45:15.000
You know, here I am.

00:45:15.000 --> 00:45:22.000
I've done everything you're supposed to do, and you're saying, what you want, boy, you better wait.

00:45:22.000 --> 00:45:27.000
And you're not even holding the conversation as to why I should wait.

00:45:27.000 --> 00:45:29.000
You're going to walk away.

00:45:30.000 --> 00:45:35.000
So the next time I go, he is no longer around, I think he's deceased maybe.

00:45:35.000 --> 00:45:37.000
The only one is there.

00:45:37.000 --> 00:45:46.000
And by this time, they are requiring you to fill out an application and give your section from the Mississippi Constitution.

00:45:46.000 --> 00:45:53.000
You copy that on to the application process, and then you interpret it.

00:45:53.000 --> 00:46:00.000
And in the application, you have to identify your precent where you would vote.

00:46:00.000 --> 00:46:07.000
And having not voted before, that's a big task.

00:46:07.000 --> 00:46:13.000
But luckily, they write the precent number on your poll tag receipt.

00:46:13.000 --> 00:46:15.000
I remember.

00:46:15.000 --> 00:46:17.000
So I put it on there.

00:46:17.000 --> 00:46:22.000
But when he looked at it, he says, not quite satisfactory.

00:46:22.000 --> 00:46:24.000
And he garrons.

00:46:24.000 --> 00:46:26.000
He walks away.

00:46:26.000 --> 00:46:28.000
No conversation.

00:46:28.000 --> 00:46:31.000
What is your father's name told you that?

00:46:31.000 --> 00:46:33.000
Were you talking to anybody about his time?

00:46:33.000 --> 00:46:34.000
Not really.

00:46:34.000 --> 00:46:39.000
And I guess one of the reason why is I'm still working basically out of town.

00:46:39.000 --> 00:46:40.000
I'm here on the weekend.

00:46:40.000 --> 00:46:42.000
I will come on the night out of town.

00:46:42.000 --> 00:46:49.000
So I'm not really carton of the fact that others are being treated the same way.

00:46:49.000 --> 00:46:56.000
So it takes me a couple of two or three years to realize that I'm not the only one that's been given this cold shot.

00:46:56.000 --> 00:46:59.000
Did you like that but try to register?

00:46:59.000 --> 00:47:00.000
Oh yes.

00:47:00.000 --> 00:47:02.000
She did three times.

00:47:02.000 --> 00:47:04.000
She took the test three times.

00:47:04.000 --> 00:47:05.000
I took her six.

00:47:05.000 --> 00:47:08.000
I think they have recorded five times.

00:47:08.000 --> 00:47:14.000
So she was more and more females are more challenging than males.

00:47:14.000 --> 00:47:17.000
And that's the reason because they're free.

00:47:17.000 --> 00:47:20.000
The male is not free.

00:47:20.000 --> 00:47:22.000
The female is.

00:47:22.000 --> 00:47:27.000
Because she raised a question of what you mean out there in past.

00:47:27.000 --> 00:47:29.000
I know I passed it.

00:47:29.000 --> 00:47:31.000
So she's getting a little bit ficing.

00:47:31.000 --> 00:47:34.000
I said, hey, you won't get me in trouble.

00:47:34.000 --> 00:47:35.000
We've got to go.

00:47:35.000 --> 00:47:43.000
But anyway, she took it three times.

00:47:44.000 --> 00:47:51.000
And she recognized for some reason that it was the present that was hanging her up.

00:47:51.000 --> 00:48:00.000
But it also said, if you don't know the present just put in a nearest town, she wrote "Hattiesburg." which means she's met all the requirements.

00:48:00.000 --> 00:48:02.000
There is nothing that had missed.

00:48:02.000 --> 00:48:06.000
And yet he said, not quite satisfied.

00:48:06.000 --> 00:48:09.000
And she went on a wide.

00:48:09.000 --> 00:48:11.000
I can't tell you.

00:48:11.000 --> 00:48:12.000
Walks away.

00:48:12.000 --> 00:48:14.000
I took her out.

00:48:14.000 --> 00:48:21.000
So we never found out until the third court took them to Thurinland to court.

00:48:21.000 --> 00:48:29.000
We're along with about 46, four or four of the people, mainly who were teachers,

00:48:29.000 --> 00:48:32.000
were subpoenaed to be at those trials.

00:48:32.000 --> 00:48:37.000
And actually she got on a witness, and I didn't.

00:48:37.000 --> 00:48:44.000
So she claims that her witness wrote the whole thing open.

00:48:44.000 --> 00:48:47.000
And she's probably right.

00:48:47.000 --> 00:48:55.000
Because when they prosecute us, I want to thank his name.

00:48:55.000 --> 00:48:58.000
I know it, but I can't remember tonight.

00:48:58.000 --> 00:49:00.000
So who is this the federal?

00:49:00.000 --> 00:49:03.000
The federal, fifth-circle court of the appeal.

00:49:03.000 --> 00:49:04.000
The door.

00:49:04.000 --> 00:49:05.000
The door?

00:49:05.000 --> 00:49:08.000
Yeah, yeah, yeah.

00:49:08.000 --> 00:49:09.000
All right.

00:49:09.000 --> 00:49:16.000
Took her application and used it as comparison with a white gentleman of a royal spring,

00:49:16.000 --> 00:49:20.000
who was a truck driver, who could not read, could not write.

00:49:20.000 --> 00:49:26.000
He had taken the test and passed it.

00:49:26.000 --> 00:49:28.000
So he really got two applications.

00:49:28.000 --> 00:49:33.000
One from a white gentleman, one from a lady of color.

00:49:33.000 --> 00:49:42.000
He passed here, and so when he questioned him about it, I think, of course I'm not in there.

00:49:42.000 --> 00:49:44.000
They said, there's a white race on you.

00:49:44.000 --> 00:49:46.000
He said, I haven't run a race.

00:49:46.000 --> 00:49:47.000
What color are you?

00:49:47.000 --> 00:49:54.000
Oh, I'm white.

00:49:54.000 --> 00:50:02.000
You know, it was a challenge, but then I started treating it as a cat and mouse game.

00:50:02.000 --> 00:50:07.000
Because every time I got a chance to go back in, I would go.

00:50:07.000 --> 00:50:11.000
So we got, we knew each other quite well.

00:50:11.000 --> 00:50:13.000
Because I would go, and he'd give me the test.

00:50:13.000 --> 00:50:16.000
I'd walk in and say, hey, you said, you got 15 minutes.

00:50:16.000 --> 00:50:17.000
Give me the test.

00:50:17.000 --> 00:50:19.000
All I wanted was the test.

00:50:19.000 --> 00:50:21.000
Because I was studying the Constitution.

00:50:21.000 --> 00:50:23.000
I knew it wasn't getting me on that.

00:50:23.000 --> 00:50:27.000
And he wouldn't get me on the pre-scent because you got it right here on my pole,

00:50:27.000 --> 00:50:31.000
and I actually see what I might have been made up.

00:50:31.000 --> 00:50:34.000
I really didn't think.

00:50:34.000 --> 00:50:36.000
Somebody's playing somebody, so...

00:50:36.000 --> 00:50:40.000
When you were saying the Constitution, is that something you were doing on your own?

00:50:40.000 --> 00:50:41.000
Oh, no, oh, no.

00:50:41.000 --> 00:50:42.000
It was the NAACP.

00:50:42.000 --> 00:50:43.000
That's all I wanted.

00:50:43.000 --> 00:50:45.000
No, no, it was not core, or native discipline.

00:50:45.000 --> 00:50:46.000
Yeah.

00:50:46.000 --> 00:50:47.000
There was all my own.

00:50:47.000 --> 00:50:50.000
How did you all find out about the lawsuit?

00:50:50.000 --> 00:50:51.000
We were subpoenaed.

00:50:51.000 --> 00:50:54.000
So that was the first you heard about it with the municipality?

00:50:54.000 --> 00:50:58.000
No, we had taught, I guess, they had interviewed us.

00:50:58.000 --> 00:50:59.000
I'm not sure.

00:50:59.000 --> 00:51:04.000
At that point, we were aware that it was going to get to the point, the Fifth Circuit Court of Appeal.

00:51:04.000 --> 00:51:06.000
But we had been in an interview.

00:51:06.000 --> 00:51:13.000
I know that when they were doing that case, and they were doing similar, a couple similar cases,

00:51:13.000 --> 00:51:17.000
they would try to subpoena the records, and they were having trouble getting me the records

00:51:17.000 --> 00:51:19.000
from the Circuit Court office.

00:51:20.000 --> 00:51:27.000
