00:51:35.000 --> 00:51:43.000
He had been in court before, had been ordered to stop making the difference between races, but he never stopped.

00:51:43.000 --> 00:51:46.000
So the records were the way they threw it.

00:51:47.000 --> 00:51:49.000
I knew that they really pursued it with him.

00:51:55.000 --> 00:51:58.000
Did you ever work with my drivers?

00:51:58.000 --> 00:51:59.000
Did you mean that?

00:51:59.000 --> 00:52:02.000
I do make, in fact, I was in school at all, or with my kids.

00:52:02.000 --> 00:52:03.000
So he was there at the time?

00:52:03.000 --> 00:52:05.000
Yeah, he was in the same time.

00:52:05.000 --> 00:52:06.000
He was finishing up there.

00:52:06.000 --> 00:52:10.000
Yeah, his wife and I were in the same class.

00:52:11.000 --> 00:52:19.000
I finished in the summer, and when I left the campus, he gave me a ride from the campus.

00:52:19.000 --> 00:52:26.000
So I had contact with him, and then of course, as I got more involved in NAACP,

00:52:26.000 --> 00:52:30.000
we had much more interaction from that level.

00:52:31.000 --> 00:52:34.000
I got a little bit involved with the NAACP, then.

00:52:34.000 --> 00:52:41.000
Well, the president of this kind of branch at that time was J.C. Fairley.

00:52:41.000 --> 00:52:43.000
We attended the same church.

00:52:43.000 --> 00:52:48.000
So this is where my first connection came with membership within NAACCP.

00:52:51.000 --> 00:52:56.000
So would he speak at church, or would you talk to people after church about it?

00:52:57.000 --> 00:52:58.000
Which JC would?

00:52:58.000 --> 00:53:01.000
Yeah, he was quite a spokesman.

00:53:01.000 --> 00:53:05.000
Yeah, and you just put me in the side of John.

00:53:05.000 --> 00:53:11.000
It didn't take a whole lot, really, and true, but just one request in I mean it.

00:53:11.000 --> 00:53:13.000
What was your motivation?

00:53:16.000 --> 00:53:20.000
I know it seems obvious, but it's one I'm trying to put it in.

00:53:21.000 --> 00:53:31.000
I had experience when I was in the servers that really heightened, I guess you say,

00:53:31.000 --> 00:53:34.000
that's sensitive to it.

00:53:34.000 --> 00:53:43.000
I was in Fort Eustis, Virginia, and there was a young man who was a manager from somewhere in Ohio,

00:53:44.000 --> 00:53:46.000
who was a white young man.

00:53:46.000 --> 00:53:53.000
He had been to a church near the camp, and he was invited to speak.

00:53:53.000 --> 00:54:00.000
And on the day before he went out, he asked if I would go with him out there,

00:54:00.000 --> 00:54:04.000
and I said, yeah, but then I'm sure I can go.

00:54:04.000 --> 00:54:06.000
Oh, yeah, I'm sure, I'm sure.

00:54:06.000 --> 00:54:07.000
Virginia?

00:54:07.000 --> 00:54:09.000
Yeah, Virginia, yeah, I'm sure, I'm sure.

00:54:10.000 --> 00:54:17.000
So one of the church members came over, picked us up, drove us to the church.

00:54:17.000 --> 00:54:25.000
We got there between Sunday's Goom and Worship's servers from my teenage.

00:54:25.000 --> 00:54:32.000
My habit was when I got the church, I would go inside, and we're not staying outside,

00:54:32.000 --> 00:54:34.000
unlike I saw a whole lot of people do.

00:54:35.000 --> 00:54:40.000
So I went in, and I picked up a bulldozer, and I was sitting over there looking at them, not paying attention.

00:54:40.000 --> 00:54:45.000
And he came in with tears in his eyes and says, we can't stay here, we can't stay here.

00:54:45.000 --> 00:54:47.000
That says why?

00:54:47.000 --> 00:54:49.000
We stay there, we won't have church.

00:54:49.000 --> 00:54:51.000
Oh.

00:54:52.000 --> 00:54:55.000
So they brought us back to the camp.

00:54:55.000 --> 00:54:59.000
And that's one thing that really, you know, stand out.

00:54:59.000 --> 00:55:10.000
I mean, it's just out in society, it's one thing, but in church, that's gross.

00:55:10.000 --> 00:55:13.000
What church did you use to stay away?

00:55:13.000 --> 00:55:19.000
St. James, Christian Methodist, Episcopal Church, yeah.

00:55:19.000 --> 00:55:24.000
Did, were there a lot of people in the congregation that joined the end of the list behind you?

00:55:24.000 --> 00:55:30.000
Procly everybody were problem members in that church, yeah.

00:55:30.000 --> 00:55:35.000
And if my church knows the same way, with small membership, or procly everybody,

00:55:35.000 --> 00:55:37.000
they're all members of the NAACP.

00:55:37.000 --> 00:55:43.000
We encouraged them to do that, and they will, they follow our leadership in that respect, yeah.

00:55:43.000 --> 00:55:49.000
Were you, once you joined the sacred faith in were they all the meetings?

00:55:49.000 --> 00:55:56.000
I did not attend a lot of meetings when I initially joined.

00:55:56.000 --> 00:56:04.000
At the time, I went on, I got involved, and then a little more involved doing the Freedom Sun.

00:56:04.000 --> 00:56:15.000
And we did sensitivity, especially for youngsters from the North, and it was, as we came down.

00:56:15.000 --> 00:56:23.000
Since we knew the culture, we did a lot of sensitivity training, round circus,

00:56:23.000 --> 00:56:30.000
talking about what you can expect, or if you say this or you say that,

00:56:30.000 --> 00:56:35.000
and some eras of what, they were accustomed to calling, policemen's pigs,

00:56:35.000 --> 00:56:41.000
we say you can't do that here, you can't call them pigs, you can use something.

00:56:41.000 --> 00:56:45.000
That's just one example.

00:56:45.000 --> 00:56:53.000
They were encouraging and trained, they were cis, but then we knew where the danger spots were.

00:56:53.000 --> 00:56:59.000
We knew what comments would set people off and things like that.

00:56:59.000 --> 00:57:05.000
So we did a lot of sensitivity training, not only here, but other part of the state.

00:57:05.000 --> 00:57:13.000
I got acquainted with the president who succeeded, JC Ferler, which was Dr. C.E. Smith,

00:57:13.000 --> 00:57:23.000
he and his family, and I became more involved, more involved with the NAACP serving on committees, and things of that sort.

00:57:23.000 --> 00:57:26.000
What was the committee?

00:57:26.000 --> 00:57:32.000
I remember one, a specifically education committee, and that's what we did.

00:57:32.000 --> 00:57:53.000
We certainly own a baratia committee in helping the city school develop a strategy for integrating the schools.

00:57:53.000 --> 00:57:57.000
Was that before or after freedom?

00:57:57.000 --> 00:58:01.000
Probably after freedom summer.

00:58:01.000 --> 00:58:03.000
Yes, yes, yeah.

00:58:03.000 --> 00:58:07.000
And at that point, are you teaching at Rowan?

00:58:07.000 --> 00:58:11.000
Lillie Burney School School.

00:58:11.000 --> 00:58:17.000
And then Rowan I were in 1969, that's when I started.

00:58:17.000 --> 00:58:19.000
Lillie Burney School School, all great slow.

00:58:19.000 --> 00:58:23.000
The two places, yeah.

00:58:23.000 --> 00:58:27.000
We were just talking to Mr. Smith earlier today.

00:58:27.000 --> 00:58:35.000
So what was it that got you more involved, you know, or do you really want to become more involved?

00:58:35.000 --> 00:58:39.000
My tutor.

00:58:39.000 --> 00:58:51.000
We had two daughters, and I did not want them to inherit what I inherited.

00:58:51.000 --> 00:58:55.000
So everything I did was with them in my...

00:58:55.000 --> 00:58:58.000
How old were they in summer 64?

00:58:58.000 --> 00:59:02.000
My oldest was born in 59.

00:59:02.000 --> 00:59:04.000
No, no, no, no, 57.

00:59:04.000 --> 00:59:07.000
The baby was born in 59.

00:59:07.000 --> 00:59:09.000
Did they go to freedom schools?

00:59:09.000 --> 00:59:11.000
No, they didn't go to freedom schools.

00:59:11.000 --> 00:59:13.000
You kept them home.

00:59:13.000 --> 00:59:15.000
You kept them home.

00:59:15.000 --> 00:59:17.000
Now, we're not worried.

00:59:17.000 --> 00:59:21.000
We did for them what they needed to have done.

00:59:21.000 --> 00:59:25.000
We're not worried about that.

00:59:25.000 --> 00:59:29.000
I just want to keep on at home.

00:59:29.000 --> 00:59:32.000
Yeah.

00:59:32.000 --> 00:59:38.000
Well, that didn't stop us from working with the freedom summer.

00:59:38.000 --> 00:59:46.000
Without church, provided houses, and for some of them, provided meals for some of them.

00:59:46.000 --> 00:59:50.000
So we were involved, but we didn't put our shoes on out there.

00:59:50.000 --> 00:59:52.000
We were involved.

00:59:52.000 --> 00:59:54.000
What are some of the things that you were all were doing?

00:59:54.000 --> 00:59:56.000
I mean, you just said housing.

00:59:56.000 --> 01:00:00.000
Can you give me a sort of a sense of what the day-to-day was like?

01:00:00.000 --> 01:00:02.000
Well, not...

01:00:08.000 --> 01:00:15.000
Of course, you know that there were leaders identified as leaders who were at various churches,

01:00:15.000 --> 01:00:20.000
where the students would come in and have the classes.

01:00:20.000 --> 01:00:24.000
And so, my provide me for them in some form of recognition,

01:00:24.000 --> 01:00:30.000
which is like a regular school, but mostly dealing with a civics citizenship.

01:00:30.000 --> 01:00:34.000
I guess we're backing up before freedom summer.

01:00:34.000 --> 01:00:42.000
When did you meet or work with any of the young people that came in with SNCC or COPE,

01:00:42.000 --> 01:00:47.000
like Hollywood Walkings or E&C,

01:00:47.000 --> 01:00:50.000
that I was too damaged on.

01:00:50.000 --> 01:00:58.000
I did not work with those persons,

01:00:58.000 --> 01:01:02.000
per se, knew about them, but...

01:01:06.000 --> 01:01:10.000
Wasn't there any other extra ones coming in?

01:01:10.000 --> 01:01:12.000
Yeah, yeah.

01:01:12.000 --> 01:01:19.000
I think the biggest portion of my involvement was doing the sensitivity training,

01:01:19.000 --> 01:01:21.000
and things like that.

01:01:21.000 --> 01:01:23.000
Sure, that was the community.

01:01:23.000 --> 01:01:25.000
Yeah.

01:01:25.000 --> 01:01:27.000
But the expectations were, how do you say?

01:01:27.000 --> 01:01:29.000
Can you...

01:01:29.000 --> 01:01:33.000
So, the biracial community,

01:01:33.000 --> 01:01:39.000
said you were working on a plan or a strategy for disavagating the schools,

01:01:39.000 --> 01:01:43.000
what were those meetings like?

01:01:43.000 --> 01:01:48.000
I learned early in my involvement that the meetings there were,

01:01:48.000 --> 01:01:53.000
the meetings that were 10 were the second meetings.

01:01:53.000 --> 01:01:57.000
The meetings had been held prior to our meetings.

01:01:57.000 --> 01:02:04.000
So, we learned to, as people of color, to come together on our education meeting,

01:02:04.000 --> 01:02:08.000
and role play.

01:02:08.000 --> 01:02:12.000
We were proposed questions that we were going to propose

01:02:12.000 --> 01:02:15.000
and we'd have somebody respond to those questions,

01:02:15.000 --> 01:02:18.000
so that when we got in the meeting,

01:02:18.000 --> 01:02:21.000
we would be conditioned to what might have been said.

01:02:21.000 --> 01:02:26.000
And also, we suggest a question that might be coming to us,

01:02:26.000 --> 01:02:30.000
be prepared to answer those.

01:02:30.000 --> 01:02:33.000
Specifically, remember Dr. Spinks,

01:02:33.000 --> 01:02:35.000
who was Superintendent of the School,

01:02:35.000 --> 01:02:37.000
and Mr. D. R. Patrick, was,

01:02:37.000 --> 01:02:41.000
I believe who was principal of

01:02:42.000 --> 01:02:45.000
Blair High School School, Mrs. Erling Boas,

01:02:45.000 --> 01:02:49.000
who was the chair of our education committee.

01:02:49.000 --> 01:02:51.000
I'm a minister, I don't know if I'm going to come in.

01:02:51.000 --> 01:02:53.000
I'm going to try to remember with other person,

01:02:53.000 --> 01:02:57.000
but I remember in meetings where these two particular

01:02:57.000 --> 01:02:59.000
gentlemen were involved.

01:02:59.000 --> 01:03:03.000
D. R. Patrick was a man of...

01:03:03.000 --> 01:03:09.000
I was a hyper-tanchor.

01:03:09.000 --> 01:03:15.000
And he was free with his emotion.

01:03:15.000 --> 01:03:21.000
He was stand up and put his finger in your face.

01:03:21.000 --> 01:03:26.000
Erling Boas was chair of that committee.

01:03:26.000 --> 01:03:30.000
And she said, don't point your finger in my face.

01:03:30.000 --> 01:03:33.000
He may take it down, but the next three minutes is back up there,

01:03:33.000 --> 01:03:36.000
and then she would put her right in his face.

01:03:37.000 --> 01:03:43.000
So we spent a lot of time trying to make sure.

01:03:43.000 --> 01:03:47.000
Trying to manage the people within the meeting

01:03:47.000 --> 01:03:53.000
so that we get to some point that we can do some positive.

01:03:53.000 --> 01:04:02.000
But anyway, they weren't interested in meetings.

01:04:02.000 --> 01:04:08.000
But the challenge.

01:04:08.000 --> 01:04:11.000
You can even go back to that fire in your head

01:04:11.000 --> 01:04:14.000
and think about what you hoped would come out of it.

01:04:14.000 --> 01:04:17.000
Obviously, you lived all these years in the scene

01:04:17.000 --> 01:04:19.000
and how it's turned out.

01:04:19.000 --> 01:04:26.000
Do you remember what your hopes were at the time?

01:04:26.000 --> 01:04:31.000
We used the word freedom and we used it all to loosely.

01:04:31.000 --> 01:04:37.000
But without tying it down, I'm not sure we knew what the word freedom

01:04:37.000 --> 01:04:40.000
encompassed.

01:04:40.000 --> 01:04:44.000
Freedom of expression, freedom to go to school wherever you want to go.

01:04:44.000 --> 01:04:48.000
Free from being harassed.

01:04:48.000 --> 01:04:54.000
We were harassed. We were terrorized.

01:04:54.000 --> 01:04:57.000
The word terrorist is not new.

01:04:57.000 --> 01:05:03.000
We lived it all our lives.

01:05:03.000 --> 01:05:08.000
Did you have direct threats on your family?

01:05:08.000 --> 01:05:12.000
No, not really.

01:05:12.000 --> 01:05:19.000
My wife had a call doing the trial at Reveal World.

01:05:19.000 --> 01:05:24.000
She said, I don't know what you were thinking about this

01:05:24.000 --> 01:05:27.000
court situation.

01:05:27.000 --> 01:05:33.000
She said, my thoughts are reserved to you.

01:05:33.000 --> 01:05:40.000
During the trial.

01:05:40.000 --> 01:05:48.000
I wasn't every day in the quarters of the courthouse.

01:05:48.000 --> 01:05:53.000
There was a white gentleman.

01:05:53.000 --> 01:05:58.000
We happened to be me, and it happened with the whole entire.

01:05:58.000 --> 01:06:03.000
It was intending to put a shoulder into me.

01:06:03.000 --> 01:06:06.000
Of course, I realized what he was doing.

01:06:06.000 --> 01:06:09.000
When he got to the point, he wanted to put the shoulder.

01:06:09.000 --> 01:06:12.000
I was just slide away.

01:06:12.000 --> 01:06:16.000
He didn't want to go into the whole entire world.

01:06:16.000 --> 01:06:21.000
Right where the city jail is now was a park and

01:06:21.000 --> 01:06:24.000
put much parking meters in front of it.

01:06:24.000 --> 01:06:28.000
My car was an apporacan lot.

01:06:28.000 --> 01:06:31.000
When I went out of the courthouse,

01:06:31.000 --> 01:06:35.000
I saw a pickup truck.

01:06:35.000 --> 01:06:40.000
I got standing outside, talking to the morning side.

01:06:40.000 --> 01:06:43.000
I got in my car.

01:06:43.000 --> 01:06:46.000
I came right by them.

01:06:46.000 --> 01:06:49.000
That way you get two length everywhere.

01:06:49.000 --> 01:06:56.000
I came right here at the corner of the post office,

01:06:56.000 --> 01:07:01.000
turning left on the pile, went to Main and turned right.

01:07:01.000 --> 01:07:06.000
Then I noticed a pickup following me.

01:07:06.000 --> 01:07:10.000
When I got down to Walnut Street,

01:07:10.000 --> 01:07:14.000
I used to be a traffic light just across the river over there.

01:07:14.000 --> 01:07:19.000
I hesitated until the green went off in caution,

01:07:19.000 --> 01:07:21.000
and I ran into caution.

01:07:21.000 --> 01:07:24.000
They ran in red light to follow me.

01:07:24.000 --> 01:07:29.000
When I got down to Katie,

01:07:29.000 --> 01:07:34.000
I Katie, hauled across the Winoboam Katie.

01:07:34.000 --> 01:07:39.000
I lived a whole, but I lived on the east side.

01:07:39.000 --> 01:07:42.000
I took Katie and I went west.

01:07:42.000 --> 01:07:44.000
They followed me.

01:07:44.000 --> 01:07:47.000
All of a sudden I just hit my brakes real quick,

01:07:47.000 --> 01:07:54.000
pulled the side and accept them noticing they would have right over me.

01:07:54.000 --> 01:07:59.000
I got off full and then when they passed me,

01:07:59.000 --> 01:08:02.000
I just followed them.

01:08:02.000 --> 01:08:06.000
At the point I stopped and I turned right and came back.

01:08:06.000 --> 01:08:11.000
They just went, I got one call at one time.

01:08:11.000 --> 01:08:16.000
It's about to ask me something about the kings

01:08:16.000 --> 01:08:19.000
and made the rocket tour to Mark.

01:08:19.000 --> 01:08:23.000
I hear that he, what did he say?

01:08:23.000 --> 01:08:24.000
Excuse me, I was right.

01:08:24.000 --> 01:08:26.000
I hear that he sucks.

01:08:26.000 --> 01:08:30.000
I said, you probably know he probably had you last night.

01:08:30.000 --> 01:08:35.000
I didn't understand.

01:08:35.000 --> 01:08:37.000
I didn't understand.

01:08:37.000 --> 01:08:41.000
He just said, your life was quick.

01:08:41.000 --> 01:08:43.000
I guess you practiced on each other.

01:08:43.000 --> 01:08:46.000
I learned from her.

01:08:46.000 --> 01:08:49.000
She taught you how to talk back.

01:08:49.000 --> 01:08:50.000
I'm not sure.

01:08:50.000 --> 01:08:53.000
Eve asked you, can you say what your wife's name is?

01:08:53.000 --> 01:08:54.000
Carey.

01:08:54.000 --> 01:08:55.000
Carey.

01:08:55.000 --> 01:08:58.000
See, ARRI, Bradley, like a...

01:08:58.000 --> 01:09:04.000
Carey Bradley, and it seems like you two are well matched.

01:09:04.000 --> 01:09:08.000
We have, we have been, now we're getting to the point

01:09:08.000 --> 01:09:14.000
where we want to be left alone now.

01:09:14.000 --> 01:09:17.000
After 60 years.

01:09:17.000 --> 01:09:22.000
We retired from pay jobs, but we never retired

01:09:22.000 --> 01:09:26.000
from working in a community, working in WACP

01:09:26.000 --> 01:09:30.000
and in the church, mission, how we're going to all that kind of stuff.

01:09:30.000 --> 01:09:32.000
We never retired from that.

01:09:32.000 --> 01:09:36.000
But, in fact, we had got more rest when we got paid for it.

01:09:36.000 --> 01:09:39.000
I was going to say, that's why you're so young.

01:09:39.000 --> 01:09:41.000
I didn't know.

01:09:41.000 --> 01:09:53.000
When you mentioned Dr. Smith, and you just now mentioned Mr. Dr. King,

01:09:53.000 --> 01:10:00.000
we were talking to Mr. Smith, and we heard a story about her sneaking Dr. King into town.

01:10:00.000 --> 01:10:04.000
But we didn't actually get her to tell that story on tape, do you know about it?

01:10:04.000 --> 01:10:08.000
I know about it, but I have to let somebody else tell it.

01:10:08.000 --> 01:10:11.000
Unfortunately, I didn't stay for the meeting.

01:10:11.000 --> 01:10:13.000
He was late.

01:10:13.000 --> 01:10:17.000
And of course, at that time, I was working, I think, in Waynesboro,

01:10:17.000 --> 01:10:20.000
And having to get up early in the morning to drive there,

01:10:20.000 --> 01:10:27.000
I didn't get a chance to stay because I went home and got some rest so I can get up to the next morning.

01:10:27.000 --> 01:10:29.000
And that's what happened.

01:10:29.000 --> 01:10:35.000
Do you know the story of how she smucked him in?

01:10:35.000 --> 01:10:39.000
I've heard the story, but I don't know if I've heard it from her.

01:10:39.000 --> 01:10:40.000
Okay.

01:10:40.000 --> 01:10:42.000
So I bet us all to leave it.

01:10:42.000 --> 01:10:44.000
Or it is there.

01:10:44.000 --> 01:10:45.000
Okay.

01:10:45.000 --> 01:10:47.000
Yeah, I'm sorry.

01:10:47.000 --> 01:10:49.000
You didn't hear the tell.

01:10:49.000 --> 01:10:54.000
What was that about, right?

01:10:54.000 --> 01:10:59.000
What did you hope school desegregation would work like?

01:10:59.000 --> 01:11:03.000
What were you working for on the committee trying to accomplish?

01:11:03.000 --> 01:11:06.000
Better supplies.

01:11:06.000 --> 01:11:10.000
I think that was better supplies.

01:11:10.000 --> 01:11:19.000
And I don't think I was expecting...

01:11:19.000 --> 01:11:27.000
Because I felt that teachers were doing a pretty good job.

01:11:27.000 --> 01:11:32.000
Could be a better job if they had the equipment and supplies.

01:11:32.000 --> 01:11:39.000
We never had a poor lab.

01:11:39.000 --> 01:11:47.000
I told you earlier we would use some books that would ten years old, something.

01:11:53.000 --> 01:11:56.000
Supplies equipment.

01:11:57.000 --> 01:12:04.000
I was not necessarily thinking about...

01:12:04.000 --> 01:12:08.000
I want to say rubbing shoulders with other races and so forth.

01:12:08.000 --> 01:12:10.000
Just give us a fly.

01:12:10.000 --> 01:12:15.000
Let us go where...

01:12:15.000 --> 01:12:25.000
Why did I have to leave Hadisburg together a graduate degree?

01:12:25.000 --> 01:12:30.000
I think that was uncalled for.

01:12:30.000 --> 01:12:37.000
That this university closed a college terms and they had graduate programs.

01:12:37.000 --> 01:12:40.000
And it didn't make sense to you.

01:12:40.000 --> 01:12:46.000
The state would give you a little money to go to a school outside of the state.

01:12:46.000 --> 01:12:48.000
You have to come up with a restaurant.

01:12:48.000 --> 01:12:50.000
Fortunately I had been in service.

01:12:50.000 --> 01:12:54.000
So I got my G.I. bill to help me out in there.

01:12:55.000 --> 01:13:01.000
People of color didn't do too bad with what they had.

01:13:01.000 --> 01:13:06.000
There have been some backlash.

01:13:06.000 --> 01:13:13.000
There have been some false notion as to what freedom means.

01:13:17.000 --> 01:13:23.000
There is a lot of motivation that we did on our own that we are not doing any.

01:13:23.000 --> 01:13:28.000
But now...

01:13:28.000 --> 01:13:33.000
I use the term freedom I never has been, never will be.

01:13:33.000 --> 01:13:39.000
Freedom you think you have can be lost if you do nothing.

01:13:39.000 --> 01:13:46.000
Because freedom incurs a huge responsibility.

01:13:46.000 --> 01:13:49.000
You've got to get uncomfortable.

01:13:49.000 --> 01:13:52.000
You've got to get tired.

01:13:52.000 --> 01:13:55.000
And I said, hey, I got it made.

01:13:55.000 --> 01:13:58.000
I said that cheer that's killing me right now.

01:13:58.000 --> 01:14:01.000
I'd have been there 10 years ago.

01:14:01.000 --> 01:14:05.000
So you need to be doing something.

01:14:05.000 --> 01:14:12.000
And there is enough blame to go around to everybody who put on my dress.

01:14:12.000 --> 01:14:18.000
Everybody who put on pants.

01:14:18.000 --> 01:14:25.000
When it comes to the life of proper exercise and your responsibility as a resource.

01:14:25.000 --> 01:14:28.000
We just take voting for example.

01:14:28.000 --> 01:14:34.000
When I didn't have the car a hunger, a thirst for it.

01:14:34.000 --> 01:14:37.000
I used my hand.

01:14:37.000 --> 01:14:39.000
I had a struggle for it though.

01:14:39.000 --> 01:14:44.000
But now that 30 seconds out, three minutes you've got it already in your hand.

01:14:44.000 --> 01:14:46.000
What is it?

01:14:46.000 --> 01:14:48.000
Angle count.

01:14:48.000 --> 01:14:50.000
There's a specific video card still.

01:14:50.000 --> 01:14:52.000
I've got a card.

01:14:52.000 --> 01:14:54.000
You've got a vote ID.

01:14:54.000 --> 01:14:57.000
No, well, vote ID is something.

01:14:57.000 --> 01:15:00.000
I don't know what they do with that.

01:15:00.000 --> 01:15:04.000
But they give you a vote restoration card.

01:15:04.000 --> 01:15:08.000
Yeah, they may let so you...most time.

01:15:08.000 --> 01:15:14.000
But I think...

01:15:15.000 --> 01:15:20.000
And I keep using the word false notion of freedom.

01:15:20.000 --> 01:15:28.000
It's been the biggest disappointment that I see.

01:15:28.000 --> 01:15:37.000
So if you don't struggle for it, you really don't have the same appreciation as people who struggle.

01:15:37.000 --> 01:15:39.000
Well, I've got to drive my dad's car.

01:15:39.000 --> 01:15:43.000
Couldn't care anything about tires.

01:15:43.000 --> 01:15:46.000
I had to worry about the oil though.

01:15:46.000 --> 01:15:48.000
He taught me.

01:15:48.000 --> 01:15:51.000
Pay attention to the oil and water in my car.

01:15:51.000 --> 01:15:53.000
Oil and water.

01:15:53.000 --> 01:15:54.000
Oil and water.

01:15:54.000 --> 01:15:56.000
Never said a thing about tires.

01:15:56.000 --> 01:15:58.000
Never said a thing about gas.

01:15:58.000 --> 01:16:03.000
I'm not going to run that.

01:16:03.000 --> 01:16:07.000
Yeah, because if the tires blow out, you're going to stop.

01:16:07.000 --> 01:16:09.000
If the gas can't stop.

01:16:09.000 --> 01:16:14.000
But it'll keep running without water and oil until it burns.

01:16:14.000 --> 01:16:19.000
It took me a long time to understand why he said that and didn't say the other.

01:16:19.000 --> 01:16:23.000
But he was training.

01:16:23.000 --> 01:16:32.000
Did you end up LACP trying to recruit the first students who went to a free amount of choice for their families who are going to?

01:16:32.000 --> 01:16:35.000
Sure, there was some recruitment.

01:16:35.000 --> 01:16:40.000
I don't think the recruitment was not that difficult.

01:16:40.000 --> 01:16:43.000
Everybody was in the same boat.

01:16:43.000 --> 01:16:50.000
Everybody was either hungry or thirsty for education in the same boat.

01:16:50.000 --> 01:16:59.000
And education was the ticket for the way out.

01:16:59.000 --> 01:17:04.000
We live in a society today.

01:17:04.000 --> 01:17:07.000
We have to cut wood.

01:17:07.000 --> 01:17:10.000
Who has to bring water in?

01:17:10.000 --> 01:17:14.000
Who has to take care of all the chickens' cars?

01:17:14.000 --> 01:17:17.000
Who has to worry about the water?

01:17:17.000 --> 01:17:19.000
He just flippled the switch.

01:17:19.000 --> 01:17:22.000
He got it comfortable.

01:17:22.000 --> 01:17:25.000
All the things that we want we can get.

01:17:25.000 --> 01:17:29.000
And the things that this has no eyes.

01:17:29.000 --> 01:17:33.000
Poverty has no eyes.

01:17:33.000 --> 01:17:44.000
People who have not been somehow educated either in the schools or the family or whatever.

01:17:44.000 --> 01:17:47.000
Basically get what they want.

01:17:47.000 --> 01:17:52.000
Or somebody else will give them what they need.

01:17:52.000 --> 01:17:59.000
And the worst is the incentive to do better.

01:17:59.000 --> 01:18:07.000
But we're free.

01:18:07.000 --> 01:18:10.000
I visit it and this is different.

01:18:10.000 --> 01:18:17.000
Part of my job initially with the federal government was to visit stores,

01:18:17.000 --> 01:18:22.000
whole training for how you handle food stamp, authorizing,

01:18:22.000 --> 01:18:29.000
and the state human resources.

01:18:29.000 --> 01:18:32.000
From the administrative part of the check on that.

01:18:32.000 --> 01:18:37.000
And that also took me into homes of people who got benefits and things like that.

01:18:37.000 --> 01:18:46.000
The first home I saw a cell phone with people who were needing a welfare and that kind of stuff.

01:18:46.000 --> 01:18:49.000
And it took me a long time.

01:18:49.000 --> 01:18:54.000
And of course, that's when they had these boxes in the boxes.

01:18:54.000 --> 01:19:00.000
When I finally got one, I was still a mobile and I never used it until I came over here.

01:19:00.000 --> 01:19:06.000
My wife was having to drive from mobile to you to take care of her dad at the time.

01:19:06.000 --> 01:19:09.000
But we came here that cut out 100 miles.

01:19:09.000 --> 01:19:13.000
But she still had to go some one more and I got up and said,

01:19:13.000 --> 01:19:16.000
look, I got this little phone here.

01:19:16.000 --> 01:19:17.000
Never use it.

01:19:17.000 --> 01:19:22.000
Let me hook it up in your car, turn it on, test it by calling them back in the house to see if it worked.

01:19:22.000 --> 01:19:24.000
And I tested it in it worked.

01:19:24.000 --> 01:19:28.000
I said, now if you have a problem, all you have to do is pick it up and call home.

01:19:28.000 --> 01:19:32.000
She left here, went up to 59 and 49.

01:19:32.000 --> 01:19:39.000
Got her her car, took gas up, put a purse down by the station, get tank,

01:19:39.000 --> 01:19:42.000
drove off and left it.

01:19:42.000 --> 01:19:49.000
The attendant saw it when I picked it up, opened it up, found an address, she called me.

01:19:49.000 --> 01:19:51.000
I said, okay, I come up and pick it up.

01:19:51.000 --> 01:19:58.000
She was in Georgetown, Georgetown, this is a sick to my wife when she discovered that she didn't have it.

01:19:58.000 --> 01:20:02.000
She picked up the phone the first time we ever used it, called me.

01:20:02.000 --> 01:20:04.000
So I don't have it, I said, okay, I got it.

01:20:04.000 --> 01:20:05.000
What must I do?

01:20:05.000 --> 01:20:07.000
Come back, as you can get a ticket coming back.

01:20:07.000 --> 01:20:09.000
So I'm not going to go to Mama.

01:20:09.000 --> 01:20:11.000
I'll be up in a few days and I bring it to you.

01:20:11.000 --> 01:20:15.000
It took me a long time.

01:20:15.000 --> 01:20:18.000
But this is a dragon.

01:20:18.000 --> 01:20:24.000
A lot of people losing jobs and everything because they don't know how to handle this technology.

01:20:24.000 --> 01:20:26.000
That's not part of what you asked for.

01:20:26.000 --> 01:20:27.000
I'm sorry.

01:20:27.000 --> 01:20:32.000
I'm sorry.

01:20:32.000 --> 01:20:38.000
Did you tell them participate in school and this event?

01:20:38.000 --> 01:20:50.000
So we sent them to private kindergarten and with the private kindergarten and about the time they got into the public school.

01:20:50.000 --> 01:20:59.000
Then of course, my kids was in the tenth and the eleventh grade.

01:20:59.000 --> 01:21:01.000
They went with the Hawkins Junior High School.

01:21:01.000 --> 01:21:02.000
Yeah.

01:21:02.000 --> 01:21:06.000
The other one went to Blair High School because she was a senior when we left.

01:21:06.000 --> 01:21:08.000
They were going away.

01:21:08.000 --> 01:21:18.000
So in the nitty gritty part of it, I said to her, they were not exposed to it.

01:21:18.000 --> 01:21:23.000
Do you know what the experience was like to children that were the first ones?

01:21:23.000 --> 01:21:25.000
Only what I hear.

01:21:25.000 --> 01:21:27.000
We've heard that just recently.

01:21:27.000 --> 01:21:35.000
We had a 50-year celebration of the first students who went into the elementary schools who came, who told their stories.

01:21:35.000 --> 01:21:38.000
It's not just past.

01:21:38.000 --> 01:21:47.000
Did any of the black teachers and high school teachers have any of them losing jobs when they could have unified those districts?

01:21:47.000 --> 01:21:49.000
None that I know of lost their job.

01:21:49.000 --> 01:21:53.000
The high school was a unique situation.

01:21:53.000 --> 01:21:58.000
Dr. N.R. Burger, a principal at the principal of N.R. Burger.

01:21:58.000 --> 01:22:01.000
I don't know if he has Dr. Nott.

01:22:01.000 --> 01:22:07.000
People say he did not get involved much, but he was in the politics.

01:22:07.000 --> 01:22:19.000
Where the county school teachers were dismissed, if it was known that they were a member of the NAACP, the city's teachers were not.

01:22:19.000 --> 01:22:27.000
So he saw it like a buffer between his teachers and people who would do them all.

01:22:27.000 --> 01:22:30.000
That was something that happened recently, building a town.

01:22:30.000 --> 01:22:32.000
Oh yeah.

01:22:32.000 --> 01:22:41.000
The year I was at Rowan, the student who walked out of school and marched from Rowan to over on Mobile Street.

01:22:41.000 --> 01:22:44.000
That was 6.9, of course, we were in.

01:22:44.000 --> 01:22:45.000
I went with them.

01:22:45.000 --> 01:22:49.000
I think a couple of the teachers went with, not everybody.

01:22:49.000 --> 01:22:57.000
We went as monitors to be sure that they did not agitate the policemen and things like that.

01:22:57.000 --> 01:23:01.000
It caused them to react in a negative way.

01:23:01.000 --> 01:23:05.000
For the graduation that they for some reason,

01:23:05.000 --> 01:23:10.000
who was asserted as one of the sponsors for the graduation that year.

01:23:10.000 --> 01:23:15.000
Mr. N.R. Burger invited myself to work with him, Mr. Spinks from the school building,

01:23:15.000 --> 01:23:19.000
across over to the football stadium where we were here at the graduation that night.

01:23:19.000 --> 01:23:24.000
He knew my involvement, you know, other people knew my involvement.

01:23:24.000 --> 01:23:35.000
And I guess the one of the reasons I accept an offer to do something other than teacher is because of the extent of my involvement.

01:23:35.000 --> 01:23:40.000
And I realized, of course, the other offer paid me twice as much now.

01:23:40.000 --> 01:23:41.000
It was not bad.

01:23:41.000 --> 01:23:49.000
It caused me to realize that if Dr. Spinks, at the end of the school term said,

01:23:49.000 --> 01:23:53.000
McGee, I don't have anything for you to do, I'm out.

01:23:53.000 --> 01:23:56.000
But I wouldn't make anything in the first place.

01:23:56.000 --> 01:24:00.000
Other job had the same opportunity to say the same thing, but at least I made something.

01:24:00.000 --> 01:24:03.000
So I took a chance on doing that.

01:24:03.000 --> 01:24:06.000
The teachers didn't have any tenure?

01:24:06.000 --> 01:24:09.000
No. If we decided he didn't need you.

01:24:10.000 --> 01:24:12.000
And especially if you've been involved.

01:24:12.000 --> 01:24:22.000
And because from that standpoint, I don't, you know, we didn't suffer the wrath as some of the countless did.

01:24:22.000 --> 01:24:24.000
Because of what we were doing.

01:24:24.000 --> 01:24:26.000
And who was crazier, both.

01:24:26.000 --> 01:24:29.000
There's one other thing that happened during this period.

01:24:29.000 --> 01:24:32.000
In 1962, I believe it was.

01:24:32.000 --> 01:24:35.000
Because of my activity.

01:24:35.000 --> 01:24:41.000
My wife and I were subpoenaed along with one other black man, T.F. Boyne,

01:24:41.000 --> 01:24:50.000
to go to Aberdeen, Mississippi, to be witnesses that Clyde Kennard was still alive.

01:24:50.000 --> 01:24:54.000
He was in Parchman Farm at the time.

01:24:54.000 --> 01:24:57.000
And I know, she'll forget it. We left here on the north.

01:24:57.000 --> 01:25:00.000
I think it was like December the 21st.

01:25:00.000 --> 01:25:04.000
I don't think it was 62. Very cold.

01:25:04.000 --> 01:25:06.000
The early end was supreme.

01:25:06.000 --> 01:25:09.000
I don't know. About two of the wife was supreme.

01:25:09.000 --> 01:25:11.000
Because they passed us on our way up.

01:25:11.000 --> 01:25:16.000
We got to Aberdeen. We went into the courthouse.

01:25:16.000 --> 01:25:23.000
And we sat and then brought Clyde Kennard in from the side, to near the chamber.

01:25:23.000 --> 01:25:26.000
We waited him. He waited us.

01:25:26.000 --> 01:25:28.000
Just to be witness.

01:25:28.000 --> 01:25:31.000
Now my wife and I co-star in that background. We're teachers.

01:25:31.000 --> 01:25:39.000
We could see if one of us had been subpoenaed and somebody wanted to take a retribution against it,

01:25:39.000 --> 01:25:42.000
then the other would have a job.

01:25:42.000 --> 01:25:46.000
But both we went. Not knowing what would happen.

01:25:46.000 --> 01:25:50.000
I know who's subpoenaed.

01:25:50.000 --> 01:25:54.000
Yeah, R. Jess Brown, attorney, R. Jess Brown did it.

01:25:54.000 --> 01:25:57.000
There were only two black attorneys that I knew of in the state.

01:25:57.000 --> 01:26:00.000
Jack Young and R. Jess Brown.

01:26:00.000 --> 01:26:05.000
I don't understand the purpose.

01:26:05.000 --> 01:26:10.000
Well, the government had ordered the, what the writ of papers' corpse,

01:26:10.000 --> 01:26:15.000
had ordered them to prove, show that he was still alive.

01:26:15.000 --> 01:26:17.000
I see because of the condition.

01:26:17.000 --> 01:26:20.000
Yeah, condition of even that.

01:26:20.000 --> 01:26:24.000
What did he look like at that time?

01:26:24.000 --> 01:26:26.000
He was real dark.

01:26:26.000 --> 01:26:28.000
Now I know that he's on key more something, but I mean,

01:26:28.000 --> 01:26:32.000
truly, really, a real dark, complacent.

01:26:32.000 --> 01:26:35.000
Didn't look ill.

01:26:35.000 --> 01:26:40.000
Well, from a distance, we only just waved through him,

01:26:40.000 --> 01:26:42.000
and that's it.

01:26:42.000 --> 01:26:43.000
And that was it.

01:26:43.000 --> 01:26:47.000
We had done our job, now we've come back, see that.

01:26:47.000 --> 01:26:50.000
And then I knew everything that it was involved in,

01:26:50.000 --> 01:26:54.000
but I had not personally met him.

01:26:54.000 --> 01:27:00.000
Did you know, how just Brown, did you know, I'm several years old?

01:27:00.000 --> 01:27:05.000
I knew him from trials, he and Jack Young had held here.

01:27:05.000 --> 01:27:09.000
So they knew you because of the voter registration.

01:27:09.000 --> 01:27:13.000
I'm sure, I'm sure, I'm sure that's it.

01:27:13.000 --> 01:27:15.000
I never knew about that.

01:27:15.000 --> 01:27:17.000
I'd never heard about that.

01:27:17.000 --> 01:27:22.000
I was going to witness that he was still living.

01:27:22.000 --> 01:27:25.000
Did you know Vernon Dahmer?

01:27:25.000 --> 01:27:30.000
I knew Vernon Dahmer, but I knew him primarily through his sons.

01:27:30.000 --> 01:27:34.000
Two of his sons were class mates with me at all.

01:27:34.000 --> 01:27:41.000
Vernon Dahmer., and we call him Vernon Dahmer, we call him Vernon Dahmer.

01:27:41.000 --> 01:27:44.000
We call Vernon Dahmer. Vernon Dahmer, that's what they call him.

01:27:44.000 --> 01:27:47.000
And Vernon Dahmer, we call him Vernon Dahmer.

01:27:47.000 --> 01:27:51.000
Sure, I remember them quite vividly before, while I was in school.

01:27:51.000 --> 01:27:53.000
Then when I came here, of course, they were in service,

01:27:53.000 --> 01:27:57.000
called they left school and volunteered for the service.

01:27:57.000 --> 01:28:01.000
And I stayed and finished my time.

01:28:01.000 --> 01:28:05.000
I didn't have the connection with him personally, personally,

01:28:05.000 --> 01:28:13.000
that others had, but one experience after he expired.

01:28:13.000 --> 01:28:17.000
And there's nobody else to verify, except for me.

01:28:17.000 --> 01:28:22.000
Several of us volunteered to just go up that way,

01:28:22.000 --> 01:28:26.000
park side the highway and just observe.

01:28:26.000 --> 01:28:30.000
And Mr. Charles, Phillip and myself drove up there together one night,

01:28:30.000 --> 01:28:36.000
shortly after they burned his house, and stood watch.

01:28:36.000 --> 01:28:47.000
Can you describe sort of a community reaction when they burned his house, killed him?

01:28:47.000 --> 01:28:50.000
A lot of sadness, of course.

01:28:50.000 --> 01:28:54.000
A lot of sadness.

01:28:54.000 --> 01:28:58.000
That was very close to home.

01:28:58.000 --> 01:29:10.000
There were groups, a group, they called them the deep guns,

01:29:10.000 --> 01:29:20.000
and not too many people knew who they were, who was white watchman, who killed watch,

01:29:20.000 --> 01:29:25.000
for anything, this funny thing that's going on.

01:29:25.000 --> 01:29:32.000
The old other thing that happened to me, I think it was after he was killed.

01:29:32.000 --> 01:29:41.000
The old other thing that happened to me that would claim my attention right now.

01:29:41.000 --> 01:29:52.000
Somebody sprayed chemical on my lawn in the form of a cross.

01:29:52.000 --> 01:29:56.000
Was that thing that's coming?

01:29:56.000 --> 01:29:59.000
You know the baby?

01:29:59.000 --> 01:30:01.000
No.

01:30:01.000 --> 01:30:04.000
Did that worry you?

01:30:04.000 --> 01:30:08.000
Not a whole lot, but I let my wife and baby sleep in the bathroom, I sleep in the front,

01:30:08.000 --> 01:30:12.000
and I'm with her, with a rifle.

01:30:12.000 --> 01:30:14.000
Did anybody else come?

01:30:14.000 --> 01:30:16.000
Help you keep watching?

01:30:16.000 --> 01:30:19.000
I just took care of myself.

01:30:19.000 --> 01:30:25.000
Were you when they had the trials, the first trials, and actually a couple of them?

01:30:25.000 --> 01:30:32.000
I was here for the first trials, and one of the guys who was given some time

01:30:32.000 --> 01:30:38.000
was paroled by Governor (William) Waller, I believe.

01:30:38.000 --> 01:30:45.000
I wrote a letter to him how terribly it was to parten the man.

01:30:45.000 --> 01:30:52.000
I sent him a couple of sent to the editor, they did print it in the paper.

01:30:52.000 --> 01:31:01.000
I was here when the last man was sent to his trial, I'd heard all of that.

01:31:01.000 --> 01:31:05.000
Did you ever get a response from the Governor?

01:31:05.000 --> 01:31:07.000
No, no.

01:31:07.000 --> 01:31:14.000
I didn't get a reply, but it was in the mail, it was in the news.

01:31:14.000 --> 01:31:21.000
Were you surprised that they were able to get the conviction in the late 60s?

01:31:21.000 --> 01:31:24.000
Not really.

01:31:24.000 --> 01:31:27.000
I guess you say yes and no.

01:31:27.000 --> 01:31:35.000
At the beginning of the get-others, then I figured at some point that everybody

01:31:35.000 --> 01:31:40.000
would be held accountable for the misdeeds they had done.

01:31:40.000 --> 01:31:45.000
It was a conviction of...

01:31:45.000 --> 01:31:47.000
I'm not black, you know, the name...

01:31:47.000 --> 01:31:49.000
Sam Bowers?

01:31:49.000 --> 01:31:51.000
How did it...

01:31:51.000 --> 01:31:58.000
Do you have a sense of that impacted community when he was kindly convicted?

01:31:58.000 --> 01:32:02.000
I don't know if there was a relief or not.

01:32:02.000 --> 01:32:06.000
It had been so long.

01:32:06.000 --> 01:32:14.000
I remember from the time the crime, the time they convicted him, I was at that child.

01:32:14.000 --> 01:32:19.000
I was at the immediate family.

01:32:19.000 --> 01:32:32.000
The younger people would not have had that much emotion, attachment as the older people were at that time.

01:32:32.000 --> 01:32:43.000
What are the things that you would like people to know about the civil rights movement?

01:32:43.000 --> 01:32:57.000
The courage, the legacy we have, the courage to keep on keeping on in spite of the arts.

01:32:57.000 --> 01:33:09.000
Don't let their opportunity of making things better past them by.

01:33:09.000 --> 01:33:20.000
You know, we have a lot of legacy, a lot of people who invest it in what we not call freedom.

01:33:20.000 --> 01:33:33.000
And if we don't continue to invest in it, then will our future generation have to inspire them to keep going.

01:33:33.000 --> 01:33:40.000
The young people today, to hear it, is sort of like a fairy tale that couldn't happen.

01:33:40.000 --> 01:33:49.000
If I was born since then and I've gone to school and I wanted to go and live basically I wanted to live, that couldn't have happened.

01:33:49.000 --> 01:33:53.000
But it did happen.

01:33:53.000 --> 01:34:02.000
